fficers from the Siborne papers |location=London |publisher=Greenhill |isbn=978-1-85367-597-3}}\n* {{Citation |last=Glover |first=Gareth |title=From Corunna to Waterloo: the Letters and Journals of Two Napoleonic Hussars, 1801\u20131816 |location=London |publisher=Greenhill Books |year=2007}}\n* {{Citation|first1=Gareth|last1=Glover|title=Waterloo: Myth and Reality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GfpsBQAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=Pen and Sword|isbn=978-1-78159-356-1}}\n* {{Citation |last=Grant |first=Charles |year=1972 |title=Royal Scots Greys (Men-at-Arms)|publisher=Osprey |isbn=978-0-85045-059-0}}\n* {{Citation |last=Gronow |first=R.H. |authorlink=Rees Howell Gronow |year=1862 |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/3798 |title=Reminiscences of Captain Gronow|publisher=London |isbn=978-1-4043-2792-4}}\n* {{Citation |last=Hamilton-Williams |first=David |year=1993 |title=Waterloo. New Perspectives. The Great Battle Reappraised |publisher=Arms & Armour Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-471-05225-8}}\n* {{Citation |last=Hamilton-Williams |first=David |year=1994 |title=Waterloo, New Perspectives, The Great Battle Reappraised|edition=Paperback |location=New York |publisher=John Wiley and Sons|isbn=978-0-471-14571-4}}\n* {{Citation |last=Herold |first=J. Christopher |year=1967 |title=The Battle of Waterloo|location=New York |publisher=Harper & Row |isbn=978-0-304-91603-0}}\n* {{Citation |last=Haweis |first=James Walter |year=1908 |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924024320891 |title=The campaign of 1815, chiefly in Flanders |location=Edinburgh |publisher=William Blackwood and Sons |pages=[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924024320891#page/n250/mode/1up 228]\u2013229}}\n* {{Citation |last=Hofschr\u00f6er| first=Peter |year=1999 |title=1815: The Waterloo Campaign. The German Victory |volume=2 |publisher=London: Greenhill Books |isbn=978-1-85367-368-9}}\n* {{Citation |last=Hofschr\u00f6er| first=Peter |year=2005 |title=Waterloo 1815: Quatre Bras and Ligny |publisher=London: Leo Cooper |isbn=978-1-84415-168-4}}\n* {{Citation |last=Hoorebeeke |first=C. van |title=Blackman, John-Lucie : pourquoi sa tombe est-elle \u00e0 Hougomont? |journal=Bulletin de l'Association Belge Napol\u00e9onienne |number=118 |date=September\u2013October 2007 |pages=6\u201321}}\n* {{Citation |last=Houssaye |first=Henri |year=1900 |title=Waterloo (translated from the French)|publisher=London}}\n* {{Citation |last=Hugo |first=Victor |authorlink=Victor Hugo |year=1862 |title=Les Mis\u00e9rables| chapter-url=http://www.online-literature.com/victor_hugo/les_miserables/77/ |chapter=Chapter VII: Napoleon in a Good Humor | publisher=The Literature Network |accessdate=14 September 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071012165710/http://www.online-literature.com/victor_hugo/les_miserables/77/| archivedate= 12 October 2007 | url-status= live}}\n* {{Citation |last=Jomini |first=Antoine-Henri |authorlink=Antoine-Henri Jomini |year=1864 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FVdEAAAAIAAJ |title=The Political and Military History of the Campaign of Waterloo| edition=3 |publisher=New York; D. Van Nostrand }} (Translated by Benet S.V.)\n* {{Citation |last=Keeling |first=Drew |date=27 May 2015 |url=http://whartonmagazine.com/blogs/business-history-dividends-of-waterloo/ |title=The Dividends of Waterloo|accessdate=3 June 2015}}\n* {{Citation |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |year=1987 |title=The Rise and Fall of Great Powers |publisher= New York: Random House}}\n* {{Citation |last=Kincaid |first=Captain J. |year=2006 |chapter=The Final Attack The Rifle Brigade Advance 7 pm 18 June 1815 |editor-last=Lewis-Stemple |editor-first=John |title=England: The Autobiography: 2,000 Years of English History by Those Who Saw it Happen |edition=reprint |location=UK |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-14-192869-2 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRArkAr-yxoC&pg=PT434 434]\u2013436}}\n* {{citation |last=Kottasova |first=Ivana |date=10 June 2015 |url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/06/10/news/waterloo-coin-belgium-france/index.html|title=France's new Waterloo? Euro coin marks Napoleon's defeat|work=CNNMoney}}\n* {{citation |last=Lamar |first=Glenn J. |year=2000 |title=J\u00e9r\u00f4me Bonaparte: The War Years, 1800\u20131815|publisher=Greenwood Press|isbn=978-0-313-30997-7 |page=119 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0NBnAAAAMAAJ}}\n* {{Citation |last=Longford |first=Elizabeth |authorlink=Elizabeth Longford |year=1971 |title=Wellington the Years of the Sword |publisher=London: Panther| isbn=978-0-586-03548-1}}\n* {{Citation |last=Low |first=E. Bruce |year=1911 |chapter=The Waterloo Papers |editor-last=MacBride |editor-first= M. |title=With Napoleon at Waterloo |location=London |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/withnapoleonatwa00macbuoft}}\n* {{Citation |last=Lozier |first=J.F. |date=18 June 2010 |url=http://www.napoleon-series.org/faq/c_horses.html |title=What was the name of Napoleon's horse? |publisher= The Napoleon Series |accessdate=29 March 2009}}\n* {{Citation |last=Mantle |first=Robert |date=December 2000 |title=Prussian Reserve Infantry 1813\u20131815: Part II: Organisation |publisher=Napoleonic Association |url=http://www.napoleon-series.org/military/organization/c_resinf2.html|accessdate=}}.{{better source|date=June 2013}}\n* {{Citation |last=Marcelis |first=David |date=10 June 2015 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-napoleon-met-his-waterloo-he-was-out-of-town-1433894903 |title=When Napoleon Met His Waterloo, He Was Out of Town |newspaper=Wall Street Journal}}\n* {{Citation |last=Mercer |first=A.C. |year=1870a |title=Journal of the Waterloo Campaign: Kept Throughout the Campaign of 1815 |volume=1 |location=Edinburgh and London |publisher=W. Blackwood |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofwaterlo01mercuoft}}\n* {{Citation |last=Mercer |first=A.C. |year=1870b |chapter=Waterloo, 18 June 1815: The Royal Horse Artillery Repulse Enemy Cavalry, late afternoon |title=Journal of the Waterloo Campaign: Kept Throughout the Campaign o