{"title_page": "Harcha", "text_new": "[[File:Moroccan Harcha with Moroccan mint tea.jpg|alt=|thumb|Moroccan Harcha with Moroccan mint tea accompanied with honey and Moroccan Cheese]]\nThe '''harcha''' (Arabic: \u062d\u0631\u0634\u0629) is a type of Moroccan [[bread]] from [[Morocco]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Kraus|first=Reprint|title=Mission scientifique du Maroc, Archives marocaines, volumes 10 \u00e0 11|publisher=|year=1974|isbn=|location=|pages=25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ernest Leroux|first=|title=Archives Marocaines Publication De La Mission Scientifique Du Maroc|publisher=|year=1907|isbn=|location=|pages=25}}</ref> made from [[semolina]], butter and milk or water. This bread often consumed with [[Turkish coffee|coffee]] or [[Maghrebi mint tea|mint tea]] during breakfast or during snacks.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Moroccan cuisine]]\n*[[List of Moroccan dishes]]\n* [[List of pancakes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{dessert-stub}}\n[[Category:Algerian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Pancakes]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Harcha Mbesses galette de semoule alg\u00e9rienne.jpg|thumb|Harcha pancakes presented with dried figs, adghess (Algerian cheese), black olives, olive oil and fresh butter.]]\nThe '''harcha''' (Arabic: \u062d\u0631\u0634\u0629) is a [[pancake]] from [[Algeria]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Kraus|first=Reprint|title=Mission scientifique du Maroc, Archives marocaines, volumes 10 \u00e0 11|publisher=|year=1974|isbn=|location=|pages=25}}</ref> made from [[semolina]], butter and milk or water. This pancake is mainly served with [[Turkish coffee|coffee]] or [[Maghrebi mint tea|mint tea]] during breakfast or during snacks.\n\nThis pancake is one of the breads consumed during [[Ramadan]]. In other [[Provinces of Algeria|regions of Algeria]], the harcha is called ''harch\u00e2ya''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Annales de l'Institut d'\u00e9tudes orientales, Librairie d'Am\u00e9rique et d'Orient|first=|title=Universit\u00e9 d'Alger. Institut d'\u00e9tudes orientales, Volumes 13 \u00e0 14 de Annales de l\u02b9Institut d\u2019\u00e9tudes Orientales|publisher=|year=1955|isbn=|location=|pages=20, 332}}</ref> in the countryside of the hinterland of Algiers, ''ragda<ref name=\":1\" />'', ''timharchat'' in [[Kabylie|Kabylia]] or even ''mbesses''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Michael Sissons|first=|title=Durum Wheat Chemistry and Technology|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=194}}</ref> in other Algerian regions.\n\nThis bread was brought to [[Morocco]] by migrant bakers from Algeria<ref name=\":0\" /><sup>,</sup><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ernest Leroux|first=|title=Archives Marocaines Publication De La Mission Scientifique Du Maroc|publisher=|year=1907|isbn=|location=|pages=25}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Algerian cuisine]]\n* [[List of pancakes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{dessert-stub}}\n[[Category:Algerian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Pancakes]]\n", "name_user": "Jamaru25", "label": "safe", "comment": "Retrived the original text that has been modified.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harcha"}
